(
  'why-we-built-above-deck',
  'Why We Built Above Deck',
  'The story behind Above Deck — why we''re building open-source tools for cruising sailors, and what comes next.',
  '<h2>The Problem</h2><p>Every cruising sailor faces the same challenge when setting up or upgrading their electrical system: how much solar do I actually need? How big should my battery bank be? Will my watermaker work with my current setup?</p><p>The answers exist — scattered across forum threads from 2014, YouTube videos of varying accuracy, and expensive marine electricians who may or may not understand your specific boat. There''s no single place where a sailor can model their actual setup with real equipment specs and get reliable numbers.</p><h2>What We''re Building</h2><p>Above Deck is an open-source platform for cruising sailors. We started with the problem we know best: energy planning.</p><p>The <strong>Energy Planner</strong> lets you model your boat''s electrical system from scratch. Select your actual equipment — real Schenker watermakers, actual Victron panels, genuine Raymarine electronics — and see exactly how much power you need, how much solar to install, and whether your battery bank is large enough.</p><p>No spreadsheets. No guessing. No "it depends" without the numbers to back it up.</p><h2>Why Open Source</h2><p>Marine software tends to be either free-but-terrible or expensive-and-locked-down. We think there''s a better model: build useful tools in the open, let the community contribute corrections and improvements, and sustain the project through the value it creates rather than paywalls.</p><p>Every equipment spec in our database is sourced from manufacturer datasheets with provenance URLs. If a number is wrong, anyone can check our sources and submit a correction. That''s how you build trust in a community of people who depend on accurate information.</p><h2>What''s Next</h2><p>The Energy Planner is our starting point. Here''s what we''re working on:</p><ul><li><strong>Knowledge Base</strong> — Practical guides for every system on your boat, written by experienced cruisers and technically verified.</li><li><strong>Community</strong> — Discussion threads organised by topic, not lost in the noise of general sailing forums.</li><li><strong>Equipment Reviews</strong> — Real-world data from sailors using the gear, not sponsored content.</li></ul><h2>Get Involved</h2><p>This project only works if sailors contribute. Try the <a href="/tools/solar">Energy Planner</a>, tell us what''s wrong, suggest equipment we''re missing, and share your real-world consumption data.</p><p>Every correction makes the tool better for the next sailor planning their system. That''s the point.</p>',
  'builder',
  ARRAY['above-deck', 'open-source', 'community'],
  true,
  '2026-02-28T00:00:00Z'
),
(
  'sizing-your-solar-system',
  'How to Size Your Solar System for a Cruising Sailboat',
  'A practical guide to calculating your power needs, choosing the right panels, and building a solar system that actually works at anchor.',
  '<h2>Start With Your Power Budget</h2><p>Before buying a single panel, you need to know how much energy you actually use. Most sailors underestimate consumption by 30-50% because they forget about duty cycles, inverter losses, and the reality that fridges run 24 hours a day.</p><p>The honest way to do this: track every device on your boat, its wattage, and how many hours per day it runs. Our <a href="/tools/solar">Energy Planner</a> automates this calculation, but understanding the principles matters.</p><h2>The Big Consumers</h2><p>On a typical 40-foot cruising boat, these items dominate your power budget:</p><ul><li><strong>Refrigeration</strong> — 45-65W running, but with a 33-50% duty cycle, that''s 350-780 Wh/day. This is usually your single biggest consumer.</li><li><strong>Autopilot</strong> — 40-60W under sail, potentially 10-20 hours per day on passage. That''s 400-1200 Wh/day when sailing.</li><li><strong>Watermaker</strong> — 100-300W for 2-3 hours per day. High peak draw but limited runtime.</li><li><strong>Electronics</strong> — Chartplotter, radar, AIS, instruments. Individually small, collectively significant: 200-400 Wh/day on passage.</li></ul><p>A moderate cruiser at anchor typically uses 1500-2500 Wh/day. On passage, add autopilot and instruments: 2500-4000 Wh/day.</p><h2>Solar Panel Sizing</h2><p>The formula is deceptively simple:</p><p><strong>Panel watts = Daily consumption / (Peak sun hours x derating factor)</strong></p><p>Peak sun hours vary by latitude and season. The Mediterranean averages 5-6 hours in summer, 2-3 in winter. The Caribbean is more consistent at 4-5 hours year-round.</p><p>The derating factor accounts for real-world losses: panel temperature, wiring, MPPT efficiency, partial shading. Use 0.75 as a conservative starting point.</p><p>For a 2000 Wh/day boat in the Med summer:</p><ul><li>2000 / (5.5 x 0.75) = 485W of panels</li></ul><p>Round up to 500W — two 250W panels or three 175W panels.</p><h2>Panel Types</h2><p><strong>Rigid mono-crystalline</strong> are the gold standard: highest efficiency per square metre, durable, 25-year warranties. Mount on a bimini frame or arch. Brands like Victron BlueSolar and Renogy deliver consistent quality.</p><p><strong>Semi-flexible</strong> panels are tempting for curved surfaces. They work, but expect 10-15% less output than rigid equivalents and shorter lifespans (5-8 years vs 20+). Heat buildup on deck-mounted panels further reduces output.</p><p><strong>Flexible stick-on</strong> panels are convenient but compromise: lower efficiency, heat problems, and delamination risk. Use them only where rigid panels genuinely cannot fit.</p><h2>Battery Bank Sizing</h2><p>Your battery bank needs to store enough energy to get through low-production periods. The standard approach:</p><p><strong>Usable capacity = Daily consumption x Days of autonomy</strong></p><p>For LiFePO4 at 80% depth of discharge with 2 days of autonomy:</p><ul><li>2000 Wh x 2 / 0.80 = 5000 Wh = 417 Ah at 12V</li></ul><p>For AGM at 50% DoD:</p><ul><li>2000 Wh x 2 / 0.50 = 8000 Wh = 667 Ah at 12V</li></ul><p>This is why LiFePO4 has taken over the cruising world — you need 40% less capacity for the same usable energy, at a third of the weight.</p><h2>The MPPT Controller</h2><p>An MPPT (Maximum Power Point Tracking) controller is non-negotiable for any serious solar installation. It converts the panel''s higher voltage to your battery voltage while maximising power extraction.</p><p>Size your MPPT for your total panel wattage. A 500W array on a 12V system needs a controller rated for at least 42A (500W / 12V). The Victron SmartSolar range is the most popular choice in the cruising community for good reason: reliable, Bluetooth monitoring, and excellent documentation.</p><h2>Common Mistakes</h2><ol><li><strong>Not accounting for winter</strong> — If you plan to cruise year-round, size for the worst season, not the best.</li><li><strong>Ignoring shading</strong> — A shadow across one cell can cut panel output by 80%. Plan your mounting carefully.</li><li><strong>Undersized wiring</strong> — Voltage drop in long cable runs wastes energy. Use our calculator or refer to ABYC standards.</li><li><strong>No monitoring</strong> — Without a battery monitor (SmartShunt, BMV-712), you''re guessing. Install one.</li></ol>',
  'electrical',
  ARRAY['solar', 'energy', '12v', 'batteries'],
  true,
  '2026-03-01T00:00:00Z'
),
(
  'lifepo4-vs-agm',
  'LiFePO4 vs AGM: Which Battery Chemistry for Your Boat?',
  'An honest comparison of lithium iron phosphate and AGM batteries for cruising sailboats, covering cost, weight, lifespan, and practical trade-offs.',
  '<h2>The Short Answer</h2><p>If you''re building a new system from scratch and can afford the upfront cost, go LiFePO4. If you''re replacing existing AGM batteries on a budget and your charging system is simple, AGM still makes sense.</p><p>The longer answer depends on your boat, your budget, and how you sail.</p><h2>Capacity and Weight</h2><p>This is where LiFePO4 wins decisively. At 80% usable depth of discharge versus AGM''s 50%, you need significantly less rated capacity:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Need</th><th>LiFePO4</th><th>AGM</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>200 Ah usable</td><td>250 Ah (28 kg)</td><td>400 Ah (120 kg)</td></tr><tr><td>400 Ah usable</td><td>500 Ah (56 kg)</td><td>800 Ah (240 kg)</td></tr></tbody></table><p>On a 40-foot sailboat where every kilogram matters, saving 80-180 kg in the bilge is transformative. That weight was sitting at the lowest point of your boat, affecting motion comfort and performance.</p><h2>Cycle Life</h2><p>A quality LiFePO4 cell delivers 3000-5000 cycles at 80% DoD. AGM batteries typically manage 400-800 cycles at 50% DoD.</p><p>In practice, a cruiser cycling batteries daily:</p><ul><li><strong>LiFePO4</strong>: 8-14 years before significant degradation</li><li><strong>AGM</strong>: 1-2 years if deep-cycled daily, 3-4 years with careful management</li></ul><h2>Charging Characteristics</h2><p>LiFePO4 batteries accept charge at nearly full rate until almost completely full. AGM batteries taper their charge acceptance significantly above 80% state of charge, meaning the last 20% takes disproportionately long.</p><p>This matters enormously for solar charging. On a partly cloudy day with intermittent sun, LiFePO4 batteries capture far more of the available energy because they accept whatever current is available at any state of charge.</p><h2>The Real Cost</h2><p>A 200Ah LiFePO4 bank costs $1800-2200 (Victron, Battle Born, Relion). A comparable 400Ah AGM bank costs $800-1200 (Lifeline, Trojan).</p><p>But factor in replacement cycles:</p><ul><li>Over 10 years: 1 set of LiFePO4 ($2000) vs 3-4 sets of AGM ($3200-4800)</li><li>LiFePO4 is cheaper per usable amp-hour over its lifetime</li></ul><p>The catch: LiFePO4 requires a compatible charging system. If your alternator regulator, shore charger, and solar controller can''t be programmed for lithium charge profiles, you''ll need to upgrade those too. Budget $500-1500 for charging system upgrades.</p><h2>When AGM Still Makes Sense</h2><ul><li><strong>Starter batteries</strong> — Always use AGM or lead-acid for engine starting. LiFePO4 can work but offers no advantage and adds BMS complexity.</li><li><strong>Tight budget</strong> — If $800 is your total battery budget, quality AGM (Lifeline GPL series) with careful charge management will serve you well.</li><li><strong>Simple systems</strong> — If you don''t have solar and charge primarily from the alternator underway, AGM''s simpler charging requirements are an advantage.</li><li><strong>Cold climates</strong> — LiFePO4 cannot be charged below 0C without a heated BMS. If you sail in near-freezing conditions, this matters.</li></ul><h2>Practical Recommendations</h2><p><strong>Going LiFePO4:</strong> Buy from established marine brands (Victron, Battle Born, Relion, Lithionics). Ensure your BMS disconnects at low temperature and low voltage. Upgrade your alternator regulator to a lithium-compatible unit (Wakespeed WS500 or Balmar MC-614). Program your MPPT controller for the correct LiFePO4 charge profile.</p><p><strong>Staying with AGM:</strong> Choose Lifeline GPL series — they''re the standard in the cruising community for good reason. Never discharge below 50% SoC. Ensure your charging system reaches proper absorption voltage (14.2-14.4V for 12V systems). A battery monitor is essential to avoid accidental deep discharge.</p><h2>The Bottom Line</h2><p>LiFePO4 is the better technology for cruising boats by almost every measure except initial cost. The weight savings alone justify the investment on most boats. But if budget constraints are real, a well-managed AGM system will still get you across oceans — sailors have been doing it for decades.</p>',
  'electrical',
  ARRAY['batteries', 'lifepo4', 'agm', 'energy'],
  true,
  '2026-03-05T00:00:00Z'
)
